Here, we review the key forms of nanoformulations being explored for the treatment of different brain disorders (
                        Fig. 3

                        ).

Liposomes were first most reported in 1960 and first report published in 1964 by Dr. Alec D. Bangham, a British haematologist along with collaborators of Babraham Institute, University of Cambridge (Guimarães et al., 2021). Liposomes have emerged as an extraordinary class of biomimicking biomolecules with spherical phospholipid morphology having diameter in the range of 50–500 nm. The liposomes can encapsulate hydrophobic and hydrophilic drugs as they are composed of hydrophilic heads and hydrophobic tail (
                              Fig. 4

                              ) (Cardoso et al., 2022; Jaradat et al., 2024; Kong et al., 2020; Lai et al., 2021; Morse et al., 2022; Nsairat et al., 2022; Raju et al., 2023; Sercombe et al., 2015; Vanza et al., 2018; Zhang et al., 2024a; Zhao et al., 2025). In target specific drug delivery, liposomes have been extensively explored because of their non-toxic nature, biocompatibility, tuneable morphology and surface chemistry (Nsairat et al., 2022). Commercially, a number of liposome-based drugs have been used in treatment of brain disorders like Depocyt® is used to treat meningitis, Doxil® in brain tumour treatment (Juhairiyah and de Lange, 2021).
